South African Stocks Advance; Life Healthcare Climbs After Interim Results

-- B y   L a u r e n   v a n   d e r   W e s t h u i z e n
-- 
2011-05-10T15:59:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-10/south-african-stocks-advance-life-healthcare-climbs-after-interim-results.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index rose 475.78, or 1.5 percent, to 32,085.56 at the 5
p.m. close of trading in Johannesburg, the highest since May 3.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of the benchmark  stock index , jumped
7.79 rand, or 2.3 percent, to 339.99 rand, its biggest advance
since April 20. Copper rose before a report that may show
inflation eased in  China , the world’s biggest user, reducing
concern that the country will take more steps to tighten credit.
 BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining company,
climbed 6.21 rand, or 2.4 percent, to 270.72 rand, the biggest
increase since March 17.  Esorfranki Ltd. (ESR)  , a building contractor, fell 5
cents, or 2.7 percent, to 1.80 rand, its first drop in three
days. The company today said it expects to post a basic loss per
share of between 13.5 cents and 14.5 cents for the year ended
Feb. 28.  Life Healthcare Group Holdings Ltd. (LHC)  , a health-care
provider, snapped two days of losses, rising 9 cents, or 0.6
percent, to 16.49 rand. Earnings per share increased 34 percent
to 53 cents ($0.08) in the six months through March, the company
said in a regulatory filing today.  Paracon Holdings Ltd. (PCN)  , a Johannesburg-based
provider of information technology resources, gained 5 cents, or
3.1 percent, to 1.65 rand, the first increase in more than a
week. Profit rose to 29.7 million rand in the six months through
March compared with 26.7 million rand a year earlier, it said in
a regulatory filing today.  Value Group Ltd. (VLE)  , a South African transport
company, gained 6 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 4.21 rand. Profit
per share excluding extraordinary items climbed 7 percent to
56.2 cents in the year through February, the company said  in a
regulatory filing today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
